<br>
Not only will this keep you from getting hit, it will also increase the group's efficiency by reducing down time between pulls.  Essentially, the melee's DPS is being wasted while a puller is bringing mobs to camp.  If the enchanter is doing the pulling while the group is fighting then the melee are always hitting stuff and your group's efficiency moves up.  There should always be a mezzed, slowed and blurred mob in camp waiting for the tank to move to once the current mob is dead.<br>
<br>
If you're too lazy to pull then you suck and you're providing your group with a sub par enchanter who's not doing his job but there's still ways to avoid agro.  Put on other's spells and watch for the spells / procs the tank is getting.  Particle effects also help with this.  When you see the spell / proc go off or land, you know you can tash / slow.  Otherwise, tash / slow after about 5 to 10 seconds of the tank meleeing.<br>
<br>
If you're in a group and the warrior has non proccing weapons or the knight is not casting spells to draw agro, then switch groups because your tank sucks.  If you want to help them suck a bit less, you may want to cast Trickster's on them for the added hate proc.  If they complain about the Lev and attack animation then tell them to get better gear or start playing their class a bit better.  <br>
<br>
The agro increasing (visage) spells are generally useless.  You're much better off casting Boggle after you get agro than casting a visage spell before.<br>
<br>
A few tricks you can try:<br>
1.  Tash at 95%, cast Boggle and then slow<br>
2.  AE tash with yourself or the tank as the target.  Doesn't seem to draw as much agro sometimes.<br>
3.  Try the pulling trick.  Can't emphasize this enough, an enchanter who doesn't bother trying to pull is just as bad as a paladin who doesn't use stuns to keep agro.  You're just not playing your class to its full potential. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;"><br>
